Hint $ $ Work universally , i.e. consider the matrix entries as indeterminates $\:\!\rm a_{\:\!ij},b_{\:\!ij}.\,$ Adjoin them to $\,\Bbb Z\,$ to get the polynomial ring $\rm R = \mathbb Z[a_{\:\!ij},b_{\:\!ij}].\, $ In this polynomial ring $\rm R,$ compute the determinant of $\rm\, (1+A B) A = A (1+BA)\,$ then cancel the nonzero polynomial $\rm\, det(A)\, $ (valid by $\rm R$ a domain). $ $ Extend to non-square matrices by padding appropriately with $0$ 's and $1$ 's to get square matrices. Note that the proof is purely algebraic - it does not require any topological notions (e.g. (Zariski) density ). Alternatively we may employ Schur decomposition as follows $$\rm\left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rm A \\
\rm B & 1 \end{array} \right]\, =\, \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rm 0 \\
\rm B & 1 \end{array} \right]\ \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rm 0 \\
\rm 0 & \rm 1\!-\!BA \end{array} \right]\ \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rm A \\
\rm 0 & 1 \end{array} \right]\qquad$$ $$\rm\phantom{\left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rm B \\
\rm A & 1 \end{array} \right]}\, =\, \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rm A \\
\rm 0 & 1 \end{array} \right]\ \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
\rm 1\!-\!AB & \rm 0 \\
\rm 0 & \rm 1 \end{array} \right]\ \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \rm 0 \\
\rm B & 1 \end{array} \right]\qquad$$ See this answer for more on universality of polynomial identities, universal cancellation (before evaluation) and closely relation topics, and see also this sci.math thread on 9 Nov 2007.
